<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Interpret Alberta’s Season</h2>

  <p>
    A mid-September median frost does not mean every location behaves the same.
    In Alberta, local elevation and terrain can shift frost timing by weeks.
    That spread is why planting decisions are less about a single date
    and more about how much heat remains in the season.
  </p>

{% set gddJuly = null %}
{% set gddAug = null %}
{% set gddSept = null %}

{% for row in state.gdd_remaining %}
  {% if row.date == "07-01" %}{% set gddJuly = row.gdd %}{% endif %}
  {% if row.date == "08-01" %}{% set gddAug = row.gdd %}{% endif %}
  {% if row.date == "09-01" %}{% set gddSept = row.gdd %}{% endif %}
{% endfor %}

  {% if july and july.gdd %}
    <p>
      In early July, there is still meaningful seasonal heat available.
      Crops planted in early summer can often reach maturity if their heat requirement fits within that window.
    </p>
  {% endif %}

  {% if aug and aug.gdd %}
    <p>
      By August, the remaining heat typically supports only fast-maturing varieties.
      At this stage, success depends more on maturity rating than planting date alone.
    </p>
  {% endif %}

  {% if sept and sept.gdd %}
    <p>
      By September, planting decisions shift almost entirely to harvest timing
      and frost protection rather than new crop establishment.
    </p>
  {% endif %}
</section>